make κ's argument eager

This means one *less* thunk for every time you use `κ` instead of `_
=>`, instead of one *more* for every time you use it instead of
`Function.const`.

It also means that you have to *not* use it in cases where you can’t
afford to evaluate the arg up-front (recursive calls, println,
sys.error, etc.)

Also switched a couple of `_ =>`s I missed earlier.

replace `Function.const(...)` and `_ => ...` with `κ(...)

Improves readability slightly. `κ`, because this is the 'K'
of SKI fame, but `K` looks like a type parameter and `k` is just
too common and too indistinct.

'S' and 'I' also implemented, as `σ` and `ɩ`, but they're not
being used anywhere at the moment because, well, S is just plain
not useful, and `ɩ` isn't all that much nicer to read than `identity`.
But it's there, in case there's a name conflict or something.
Kill ~200 lines of unnecessary code.

Fix object-flattening ($flatMap) merging.

Fixes #488.

* Add [`$SimpleFlatMap`][†], which takes an expression (that hopefully
 evaluates to an array or object) and a function that is called on each
 entry in that array or object;
* add `coalesce`/`finalize` cases for `$Simple*Map` (`coalesce` combines
 adjacent `$Simple*Map`s, `finalize` merges `$Simple*Map`s into
 adjacent `$[Flat]Map`s);
* convert `$Unwind.flatmapop` to use [`$SimpleFlatMap`][‡]; and
* fix `toCollectionBuilder(FlatteningBuilder(Object))` to return the
 entire object, not just the flattened field and to pass the `base`
 through rather than always using `$$ROOT`.

[†]: I wanted to just replace `$FlatMap`, but since we still have
 non-simple `$Map`, `coalesce`/`finalize` can create non-simple
 `$FlatMap`s, even though we never create one directly.
[‡]: This change is potentially pessimizing, as it uses `for (i in arr) …`
 rather than `arr.map(function (i) { … })`, but this allows us to use
 the same code (IE, `$SimpleFlatMap`) for objects (which require the
 `for … in`) and arrays.
Merge remote-tracking branch 'upstream/master' into ready/445

implement `date` and `time` conversions (Fixes #445)

`Date` and `Time`, as well as `Timestamp` and `Interval`,
all become first-class values in `Data`, so that the front-end
can communicate the semantics unambiguously in the logical plan.

`Date` comparisons get special handling in the planner, since
only timestamp-equivalent values actually exist in MongoDB, but
the assumption is that people are using them to store dates in
some cases, and comparing them involves computing the end-of-day
timestamp.

`Time` values, on the other hand, become simple strings (which
happen to be comparable as is). This meant producing a rather
complicated JS expression, so our `whenDefined` scheme is
significantly beefed up. For example, we now check for the
presence of a method before calling it (with a compound test as in
`(value != null && value.getUTCSeconds != null) ? value.getUTCSeconds() ? undefined`),
but do *not* do that test in cases where it's clear that we
know what we're doing (as in `['CO', 'CA'].indexOf(state)`).

The operators in `MathLib` now accept temporal values where the
result is sensible, which flushed out quite a few bugs and corner
cases in those type checkers. There is probably more to do here,
but the current implementation supports several useful ways of combining
constants and values.

Along the way, fixed some of the worst cases associated with #571, but
there are still likely many combinations of constants and mixed types that
don't work right.

Merge pull request #574 from sellout/ready/407-parallel-flatten

Unify fields that are flattened in both multiple contexts.

Get rid of a special case in `toCollectionBuider(DocBuilder)`.

It pessimized the query (`mapReduce; aggregate` vs `mapReduce`) to avoid
projecting under `value` (avoiding some cases of #503), but also did it
poorly so that it broke a new test that showed up in the merge commit.
Merge remote-tracking branch 'upstream/master' into ready/407-parallel-flatten

Unify fields that are flattened in both multiple contexts.

Fixes #407.

This replaces the `ShapePreservingBuilder` with a new one that postpones
merging the incoming builders and adds a new `FlatteningBuilder` to
handle both the `$unwind` of `flattenArray` and the `$flatMap` of
`flattenObject` consistently and without throwing away the history of
builders.

The new `ShapePreservingBuilder` allows us to get rid of the complicated
`These` (`\&/`) contents of GroupBuilder, since we no longer have groups
that already have a document and are also having a new field built on
them. This also gets rid of a few bad/impossible states for a
GroupBuilder.

A lot of operations just “pass through” the new
`ShapePreservingBuilder`, being applied to the `src` builder, then
having the SPB wrapped around the result of that.

A few other issues were also fixed here:

* cover more cases in `merge`, `objectConcat`, and `distinctBy` (fixes #384),
* catch a bug where we weren’t rewriting a DocVar (fixes #524),
* implement delegate for `WorkflowBuilder.merge`, and
* statically check if we can `projectField` from a `GroupBuilder`.

One negative side effect is that #503 rears its head a bit more, as we
now manage to build a better `DocBuilder` rather than ending up with a
`$simpleMap` that we later tack a `$project` onto. This affects
`selectArrayElement.test`.
